To allow users to securely save and fetch their own financial data in your Firebase project, you need to set your **Firestore Security Rules** to restrict access based on the user's Authentication UID.

In your code, you are storing data at the path `users/{userId}`. Here is the exact rule configuration you should paste into the **Rules** tab of your Firestore console:

### The Recommended Firebase Rules

```javascript
rules_version = '2';

service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {

    // Matches any document in the 'users' collection
    match /users/{userId} {

      // Allows a user to read or write the document ONLY if their 
      // Authentication UID matches the document ID ({userId})
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == userId;

    }
  }
}
```

### Why this rule is correct for your app:

1.  **`request.auth != null`**: This ensures that the person trying to access the data is a logged-in user (either via Google or as an Anonymous Guest).
2.  **`request.auth.uid == userId`**: This is the critical security layer. It compares the ID of the person making the request to the name of the document. Since your app uses `doc(db, 'users', user.uid)`, this rule guarantees that User A cannot see or edit User B’s financial data.
3.  **No Public Access**: Unlike "Test Mode" rules (which usually expire after 30 days and allow anyone to read/write), these rules are production-ready and keep your users' sensitive credit information private.

### How to apply this:
1.  Go to the [Firebase Console](https://console.firebase.google.com/).
2.  Select your project: **"whats-my-credit-worth"**.
3.  Click **Firestore Database** in the left sidebar.
4.  Click the **Rules** tab at the top.
5.  Delete the existing rules and paste the code above.
6.  Click **Publish**.

